<section>
    <h1>Install Strapless</h1>
    <p>Get Strapless through npm:</p>
    <p><pre>npm install strapless</pre></p>

    <aside>
      <p>Need a <strong>file to use</strong>, not <strong>something to install</strong>?</p>
      <button type="button" class="failure" onclick="Strapless.downloadCSS();">Get the CSS version</button>
    </aside>

    <p>Or grab it off GitHub:</p>
    <p><pre>git clone git@github.com:Tivix/strapless.git</pre></p>

    <p>Strapless is designed to serve as a base for your project's Less or CSS. Download it once and start your project.</p>

    <aside class="info"><p><strong>New in Strapless v2!</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Faux two-column experience</li>
        <li>Luma-fixing on algo colors</li>
        <li>Stripped-down basics</li>
      </ul>
    </aside>

    <p>For the simplest, quickest start, just use it like an extra-thick normalize.css, adding your own styles after it.</p>

    <p>Strapless is written in Less, which is super flexible and easy to use. The best way to use Strapless is to download it and adopt Strapless's Less files and architecture as the starting point for your own project's styles.</p>

    <h3>Features</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Typographic responsiveness:</strong> Strapless isn't merely mobile-first responsive &mdash; it preserves text measure! In other words, line breaks in sections and asides will be preserved across all resolutions.</li>
      <li><strong>AA-level text contrast:</strong> AA-level text contrast <em>with any base color!</em> Whether @background is bright yellow or dark blue, the body text will meet contrast standards.</li>
      <li><strong>Semantic classes:</strong> Strapless uses six semantic classes that work on everything: Action, reaction, info, warning, success, failure.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

